\section*{Smart Cities}

The way we live has been changing quickly under the influence of the information era technologies. The cities in which we live are the next fated to follow the revolution. \emph{Connectivity} is becoming ubiquitous to modern cities and the foretold massive deployment of \emph{sensors} will soon enable us to interact with our urban environment using the same tools we now use to access information. Policy and decision makers will be supported by data of unprecedented magnitude.
\fig{smartcity}{nocaption}{.9\columnwidth}

\section*{Smart Cities on the SmartGrid}

The way we produce and distribute electricity has remained mostly
unchanged since Telsa's time. However, the recent recognition that
natural resources are being depleted faster than the planet can
replenish them drove us toward more \emph{sustainable} strategies. The
\emph{SmartGrid} combines ICT and EE technology to improve the power
grid efficiency and to enable distributed generation, the key to the
integration of \emph{clean energy} sources.  The underlying technology
shares many aspects with that for \emph{Smart Cities}.  Addressing both
challenges at once will certainly optimize the endeavor.

\fig{smartgrid}{nocaption}{.9\columnwidth}

